AGI - The United States accused Russia > of launching a spacecraft capable of attacking satellites in orbit > according to the data held by the Pentagon, while tensions on spatial weapons increase. "Russia has launched a satellite in the low Earth orbit that we believe could probably be a weapon," said the Pentagon spokesman, Pat Ryder, adding that the spacecraft was sent "in the same orbit as an American government satellite." The spokesman said that the satellite - Cosmos 2576 - was launched on May 16 by the Russian cosmodrome of Plesetsk, about 800 km north of Moscow.
&nbsp;
The Russian state space agency Roskosmos said that the launch of May 17 was "in the interest of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation". The different launch dates may be explained by the time zone. Neither Moscow nor Washington provided further details, but space analysts claim that Cosmos 2576 seems to be on the same orbit as the US satellite 314. The Kremlin spokesman Dmitri Peskov refused to comment. "We do absolutely in accordance with international law, we do not violate anything and we have repeatedly advocated the prohibition of any weapon in space," it has limited itself to answering Peskov.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
He was Deputy Foreign Minister, Serghei Ryabkov, speaking instead of "buffalo" launched by the Pentagon. The Russian space program is developing as planned, even this is not a novelty," he explained, "space vehicle launches for various purposes, including devices that solve the problem of strengthening our ability to defend". Ryabkov reiterated that Moscow "was always and constantly opposed to the deployment of attack weapons in the low Earth orbit". Since it launched a large-scale invasion of Ukraine in February 2022, Russia warned that US satellites that help the Ukrainian army could become legitimate targets. Moscow accused Washington of trying to use Space as a weapon after the US vetoed the Russian non-proliferation motion presented at the United Nations.
&nbsp;
In recent months, the world's powers have exchanged accusations on an arms race in Space and have proposed rival motions on non-proliferation at the United Nations. Russia vetoed the American initiative last month, while Monday Moscow's proposal was blocked by the United States, Great Britain and France. Space is one of the few areas in which Moscow and Washington maintained a certain degree of cooperation, despite the sanctions regime and tensions that followed the Russian invasion of Ukraine. Both countries transport their astronauts to and from the International Space Station (Iss). The dispute over space weapons revives the spectre of the militarization of Space, although the 1967 extra-atmosphere Treaty for the countries to deploy "any object carrying nuclear weapons or any other kind of weapon of mass destruction" in orbit or space.

