AGI - Recognition of a State is a legal act governed by international law. It is a unilateral decision and does not depend, in the case of Spain and Ireland, on whether or not it has the approval of the EU, which has no jurisdiction in the recognition of States. Of the 193 members of the United Nations, just over 140 recognize Palestine as a state; to these will be added Spain, Norway and Ireland. There are eight other EU members who have already taken the step, and are Sweden, Romania and Poland, but important allies such as Italy, Germany or France have not. On 10 April, the UN General Assembly adopted a resolution which recognizes Palestine as a qualified member of the United Nations, and recommends the Security Council to "reconsider the matter favorably". The text has collected 143 favorable countries. But this decision must have the approval of the Security Council and the United States oppose.
&nbsp;
<h2> Palestine meets the requirements to be a full state?</h2>
The recognition of a new state requires that there is a defined population, a bounded territory and a government that exercises authority over it. In the case of Palestine, no assumption is satisfied because there are no boundaries established internationally. Similarly, there is no government that has control over the entire Palestinian territory: the government of the West Bank is in fact exercised by the Palestinian National Authority, the leader of Gaza was Hamas until the war with Israel. For this reason, more than legally, recognition must be interpreted as a political move to encourage the peace process and support the right to self-determination of the Palestinian people. &nbsp;

